review_blob: Courtesy jsquire.  A very confused and weak malt profile, some sour notes and mild cereal taste with sweetness but nothing solid.  Hops are there, hay, grass, herbs, but the malt lacking throws the whole thing off.
A bland, underhopped, watery beer with a mild grainy sweetness.  Soapy head that fades rapidly.  Meh.
Extremely mild and nondeScript, light floral notes with possibly some corrianderbut more likely an herbal hop note.  Slightly sweet, large fizzy disappearing head, and watery finish.

A pretty standard tripel, solid without too much alcohol, a medium weight on the palate, aromas of melons and darker fruits with plenty of sweetness and slightly spicy/bitter end, aftertaste mostly dry and herbal.

Not dominated by the bourbon, which automatically gets a few points from me for not being overdone.  Rich and sweet with a ton of caramel, pecan, and vanilla tones.  Ends with a bit of peat and a little touch of hayish bitterness.  Very light mouthfeel comparatively.

The hops are pretty prominent.  I would have liked some balance from the malt, especially more intensity from the raisin and toffee flovrs, but those were dominated by a thin, grainy sweetness.  Nice color, but thin mouthfeel.

Courtesy jsquire.  Call me nuts but I enjoyed this.  Its a little too sweet and simple, reminding me more of an Ofest than a bock.  Strong caramel and  toffee taste, and weak notes of tea and hay.  Too thin on the mouthfeel and overall simplistic, but very drinkable.

Courtesy jsquire.  I was hoping like hell this was gonna be good, since I havent had a Maibock Ive really liked since Smuttynoses.  Alas, this was rather thin and uninspired.  The malt was lightly sweet but lacked thickness, intensity, or complexity of flavors.  The finish was clean but thin.

Kind of grassy-smelling, with lemon pledge and tangerine odors.  Lots of grapefruit flavor, a bit much for me.  Given the overall lightness and toastiness of the malt, I think a  more herbal hop flavor might have worked better.  This was bright and fresh, with a crisp white head and a deep yellow body.
beer_name: Full Sail Son of Spot IPA

review_blob: The spices in here are a bit muddled, but the alcohol burn falls short of unpleasant and the malt is a semi-rich, medium-sweet, thickish exploration of pumpernickel bread, molasses, and fluffy biscuits.  End is bitter with a sticky aftertaste.
beer_name: Lake Superior Old Man Winter Warmer

review_blob: Aged bottle.  The shine has gone off the hops, as expected, but the closing bitterness is still there.  There is slight toffee-sweetness and biscuit and medium mouthfeel.  Nice.

Another one from Amy.  Another interesting beer.  There are some odd herbal notes in here, I hate to say oregano, b/c thats not quite right, but thats the herb thats coming to mind.  Pair the herbs with some very staright up sugar-sweet notes and I am wondering where they are going with this.  There are also flavors of bicuit and cracker, and grassiness and some fruit.

Courtesy Amy.  An...interesting beer.  Very fruity, with some berry and melon notes, also biscuity malt.  Did not notice much alcohol flavor.  Definitely sweet witha  sticky finish.  I cant quite decide if I like the flavor combination or not.
Horrendously overbalanced, tasting of nothing but grapefruit and pine trees.  If there is malt in here, I cannot find it.
Oddly acidic for a dunkel--perhaps this was too old.  A thin big-bubbled head, fast fading.  Taste contains some soft fruits and dark malts, a little bit of raisin and maybe a hint of char.
Not as pleasing as the helles-weiss.  Soft caramel sweetness and a mid-palate metallic transition to a sharp wheat finish.  Phenols and cloves in the aroma.  Head did not last.

A pleasant beer.  A generous mix of chocolate, malt flavors, and the nuttiness that many browns claim to have, but so few actually show.  Clean finish and mild aftertaste mean it does not linger on the palate.  Very considerate of it, being that I went on to have other beers that night.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: This rating concludes the latest round of Leinies torture I have put myself through.  I have had worst Ofests, but not many.  Flat, cardboardy, spoilt caramel sweetness, with a sour, grainy finish.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: Without the "Weiss" on the label I would not have known this was a wheat beer.  Thin, not a hint of wheat anywhere, a vague sweetness reminiscent of an underhopped macro beer, and a metallic aftertaste.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: Thick, syrupy, cheap chemically cinnamon-flavor with overwhelming apple blandness.  They couldnt find an apple with any tartness?  Coating aftertaste.  Bad.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: Truly horrible example of a radler-in-a-bottle beer.  Like every Leinies beer, too sweet and reeks of artifical flavor.  How hard is it to use real lemon flavor?  Too hard, apparently.  I notice other raters have said it was at least refreshing, but it was a struggle to finish even one bottle for me.

Thanks to, I believe madsberg, for the long ago trade and his incredible patience.  Held up very well despite the storage.  A fresh, tart/fruit aroma and a nice fluffy head (though it didnt last too long).  Mouthfeel is balanced, bouncy wheat with sticky sweet, and flavors range from the typical yeast, bananas and clove to a touch of citrus and clean acidic finish.  Very nicely done.

beer_brewer_name: The Cider House / Domaine de Grand Pr
review_blob: Forgot who I got this from, sorry, but thank you to the kind soul who provided it.  Neither good nor bad, strictly speaking, but instead pretty similar to every other bottled hard cider I have ever had.  Too sweet, almost artificial in the aroma, but taste is much milder apple and tart flavors and a chalky, peely aftertaste.  Light mouthfeel and effervescent carbonation.  Know what I would like?  A cider thats sweet like an ice wine.  Guess Id better pony up for one of those Quebec ice ciders.

Too little like either a beer or a lemonade to have the thrist-quenching properties of either.  The lemon component was weakly sweet and the beer component was pale malt without the slightest bit of hoppiness.  I think they were going for a radler-type drink, but its just not very good.  Sticky, sweet, and weak flavors.

A very pale, uniformly cloudy ale with a thin white strip of head.  Small hint of spiciness and a whiff of tartness in the aroma.  Mouthfeel is light, taste is mild but pleasant, with light bitterness to start, followed by a fruity/spicy middle, and finished medium dry.  Average, but one of the few beers I have had here without any major flaws.
Light, with a very pale straw yellow color and a weak floral hop aroma.  Light mouthfeel and low carbonation.  Inoffensive but absolutely nothing of note in the flavor department.

The juniper for me appeasr only at the very end.  Up until then, I had a very short shot of sweetness to start, followed by a long and dryly bitter middle with strong herbal notes.  Then the finish with the aforementioned juniper.  Palate was medium throughout with a bitter aftertaste.  Okay.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: More bitter than I expected.  Notes of white pepper, oranges, low carbonation and medium, soft mouthfeel.  Some sweetness but quickly overtaken by dryness.  Not as complex as Id hoped.

Not particularly chocolately, and I notice no chili at all, but the overall effect is that of a delicious beer eaten with a subtle chocolate dessert that meshes with it perfectly instead of clashing.  The chocolate could be more prominent and the slight chalky aftertaste was not great, but Id drink this again without complaint.  The first recognizeably quality beer I had after a long string of mediocre rates, and I noted in relief that I did, indeed, still truly enjoy beer.

Cant believe I havent rated this.  One of the triple threat of quintessential saisons (this, Saison Dupont, and Saison de Epeautre).  This is the juicy one--sweeter than Dupont but not as estery as Blaugies, a delicious mix of sweet meadow-sun-kissed fruity/honey malt, mysterious subtle funk, and a balanced dry finish without overly harsh hopping.  Drinks like a 4% beer.  Delicious.
Quite unbalanced.  Good perhaps for hopheads but not for me.  Little if any backing malt noted.  Mostly resinous bitterness and extremely dry.

Quite big and syrupy rich, with lots of honey, fizzy/tangy fruit notes, and cereal/toast flavors.  Some interesting esters of possibly apple and spice, but mostly a big, sweet beer well balanced in the back end with a floral, Saaz-like bitterness and a dry finish with slightly sticky aftertaste.  One of the better big beers I have had in quite a while.

A bit overcarbonated, but otherwise quite solid.  NO Cascades and so the hops chosen (slightly fruity/floral/earthy, whatever they are) mesh rather nicely with the nice toffee and mild fruity flavors of the malt.  I wish there was a local ESB similar to this that I could drink regularly.

Smells better than it tastes, unfortunately.  The aroma is full of interesting things like slight barnyard, fresh-mown hay, wild summer berries, and bitter orange peel.  The flavor is somewhat alcoholic and bogged down with muddled sweetness.  Sorry to say, b/c I like Smuttynose and they generally do a nice job with their Big beer series, but this was meh.
beer_name: Smuttynose Big Beer Series: Farmhouse Ale

review_blob: Surprising.  Thin, grainy, astringent, yet manages to carry off a certain flavor profile.  Mainly a balance between simple rice sweetness, some burnt flavors, and ending bitterness.  Hmm.

One of  the best chocolate beers Ive had.  A full, dusty bittersweet chocolate taste with a medium-heavy mouthfeel and a underpinning of roast, nuts, caramel, and some cream.  Bittering is clean and the beer finishes light and not sticky.
A strange coating mouthfeel and a lot of things going on with the malt.  Caramel foremost, but also notes of grass, nuts, and some slight fruitiness.  Not quite dry enough on the finish.

A very mild rendition that ends up more cloying than refreshing.  Would prefer it to be sharper and with better attenuated flavors.  Things are kind of muddled in there.  Some orange, some coriander, some hay notes, some grass, some dust.
Against the grain here, with what I thought was a light body to carry off the sweetness and a slightly juicy bitterness that ended only medium dry.  An interesting rendition.
Kind of thin and fizzy with nominal oatmeal flavor and some chocolate and biscuit notes.  Unremarkable.
Kind a of a German-style pils, a very pale color and a fritzy light body and dry bitterness as opposed to herbal or floral.  Light body, mild malt that has touches of honey and tea flavors.  Not bad.

As everyone else has said, this has a prominent nutty component and some indeterminate nut sweetness in the middle.  A medium-dry finish.  I was quite surprised, it is unusual to find a brown that I would drink again.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: Does it need to be said?  Yuck.  Never try to handle more than one Leinies a day.  Your tastebuds will hate you for weeks afterward.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: Awful, fakey-fruit tasting swill. People around love Leinies and are always telling me I need to try this one or that one.  I do and I cannot see the appeal.  They all taste artificially flavored and uniformly bad.

Not bad really.  Much, much better than their usual wheat.  Some esters, some orangey citrus, some wheat and cloves and a decent mouthfeel.  I would prefer the malt, wheat and esters to be kicked up--the flavors are there in the right proportions but they are not intense enough.

Dry, bitter, herbal, floral, reminds me slightly of Saison Dupont but with slightly less carbonation.  Malt is subtle but hints of honey and biscuit are there along with a simple-syrup-like initial sweetness that fades to the dry middle and end.  Mild esters.  Good.

A very solid bock with hints of toffee and coffee but avoiding the cloyingness of International Coffees.  Some small nuttiness and clean bitterness with little hop flavor.  I would prefer a slightly heavier mouthfeel and more malt, but this is solid.

These guys can just do flemish sours, period.  An intriguing earthy aroma, like wet leaves and cooling earth and pumpkin pie spices.  Hints of nuts, vanilla, earthiness, dark sour cherries, winey apples, and plenty of carbonation.  Not overly sour but balances sourness with dryness and residual sweetness and some funk.  I have couple bottles of this stashed and suspect it will age well.  Very good.

Much better than expected after two years on the shelf.  A somewhat citrusy sweetness with a lightly herbal ending and a medium but not too sticky mouthfeel.  Plenty of light nut and caramel malt notes.  Very pleasant.  Thanks to Dee for this, whose grandfather used to be head brewer and who brought me a bottle two Christmases ago.  The brewery itself is interesting; they still use open fermentation and are a strongly local brand.
Light, somewhat dry, but mostly papery and flavorless.  Very slight roast flavor but no discernible chocolate.  Bland.  On nitro.
